# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-newport
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:chrysler-newport/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-newport/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
[src:chrysler-newport/astradome] The **AstraDome** was a unique, futuristic instrument cluster introduced by Chrysler Motors in its 1960 product line through 1962.
[src:chrysler-newport/astradome] It was offered only in Chrysler branded vehicles, like the Chrysler 300-F, G and H.
[src:chrysler-newport/astradome] All gauges were positioned in three dimensions under a single dome cluster.
[src:chrysler-newport/astradome] Control knobs were installed at the base of the cluster that were labeled "Rear Window" and "Map Light" on the left side and "Dome Light" and "Antenna" on the right side.
[src:chrysler-newport/astradome] The panel featured a nonglare electroluminescent illumination system combining red needles and numerals that glowed green.
[src:chrysler-newport/astradome] It was a design improvement from an instrument gauge used from 1949 until 1954 on all Chrysler branded vehicles, while adding a futuristic appearance.
[src:chrysler-newport/astradome] The approach was introduced again for 1965 and 1966 with a half-circle speedometer with gauges included below but did not extend out toward the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:chrysler-newport/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The functional design and development of a modern motor vehicle is typically done by a large team from many different disciplines also included within automotive engineering, however, design roles are not associated with requirements for professional- or chartered-engineer qualifications.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Automotive design in this context focuses primarily on developing the visual appearance or aesthetics of vehicles, while also becoming involved in the creation of product concepts.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Automotive design as a professional vocation is practiced by designers who may have an art background and a degree in industrial design or in transportation design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] For the terminology used in the field, see the glossary of automotive design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The task of the design team is usually split into three main aspects: exterior design, interior design, and color and trim design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Graphic design is also an aspect of automotive design; this is generally shared amongst the design team as the lead designer sees fit.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The design focuses not only on the isolated outer shape of automobile parts, but concentrates on the combination of form and function, starting from the vehicle package.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The aesthetic value will need to correspond to ergonomic functionality and utility features as well.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Though not all the new vehicular gadgets are to be designated as factory standard items, some of them may be integral to determining the future course of any specific vehicular models.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The design team(s) responsible for the exterior of the vehicle develops the proportions, shape, and surface details of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Exterior design is first done by a series of manual sketches and digital drawings.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Progressively, more detailed drawings are executed and approved by appropriate layers of management, followed by digital rendering to images.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Consumer feedback is generally sought at this point to help iteratively refine vehicle concepts according to the targeted market and will continue throughout the rest of the design refinement process.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] After more progressive refinement, industrial plasticine and or digital models are developed from and along with the drawings and images.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The data from these models are then used to create quarter-scale and finally full-sized mock-ups of the final design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] With three- and five-axis CNC milling machines, the clay model is first designed in a computer program and then "carved" using the machine and large amounts of clay.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Even in times of photorealistic (three-dimensional) software and virtual models on power walls, the clay model is still the most important tool for a final evaluation of the exterior design of a vehicle and, therefore, is used throughout the industry.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The designer responsible for the vehicles' interior develops the proportions, shape, placement, and surfaces for the instrument panel, seats, door trim panels, headliner, pillar trims, etc.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Here the emphasis is on ergonomics and the comfort of the passengers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The procedure here is the same as with exterior design (sketch, digital model, and clay model).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The color and trim (or color and materials) designer is responsible for the research, design, and development of all interior and exterior colors and materials used on a vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] These include paints, plastics, fabric designs, leather, grains, carpet, headliner, wood trim, and so on.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Color, contrast, texture, and pattern must be carefully combined to give the vehicle a unique interior environment experience.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Designers work closely with exterior and interior designers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Designers draw inspiration from other design disciplines such as industrial design, fashion, home furnishing, architecture, and sometimes product design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Specific research is done into global trends to design for projects two to three model years in the future.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Trend boards are created from this research to keep track of design influences as they relate to the automotive industry.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The designer then uses this information to develop themes and concepts that are then further refined and tested on the vehicle models.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The design team also develops graphics for items, such as badges, decals, dials, switches, kick or tread strips, or liveries.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The sketches and rendering are transformed into 3D digital surface modeling and rendering for real-time evaluation with Math data in the initial stages.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] During the development process succeeding phases will require the 3D model fully developed to meet the aesthetic requirements of a designer as well as all engineering and manufacturing requirements.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The fully developed CAS digital model will be re-developed for manufacturing meeting the Class-A surface standards that involve both technical as well as aesthetics.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] A Product Engineering team will further develop this data.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] These modelers usually have a background in industrial design or sometimes tooling engineering in the case of some Class-A modelers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Autodesk Alias and ICEM Surf are the two most widely used software tools for Class-A development.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Uniform surface continuity is critical to ensure Class-A surface standards.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The continuity of the areas is between the quality grades G0 through G3, with G3 guaranteeing the cleanest patch-to-patch transitions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The design process occurs concurrently with other product engineers who will be engineering the styling data for meeting performance, manufacturing, and safety regulations.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] From mid-phase, back-and-forth interactions between the designers and product engineers culminate into a finished product being manufacturing-ready.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Apart from this the engineering team parallelly works in the following areas.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Product Engineering (Body In White Sheetmetal Design and Plastic engineering), NVH Development team, Prototype development, Powertrain engineering, Physical Vehicle validation, Tool and Die development, and Manufacturing process design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The design team for a specific model consists of a chief designer and an exterior as well as an interior designer.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] In some cases, all three roles are done by one designer.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Several junior designers are involved in the development process as well and make specific contributions all overseen by the chief designer.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Apart from this, the color and trim designer works closely with other designers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The clay model team and digital model team work closely with the styling team all located within the studio.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Apart from this, there would be studio heads, studio managers, and prototype engineers who would work across all teams in the studio.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The total team size for developing a full car usually ranges from 25 to 40 members and the development time lasts for more than 24 months until signed-off for tooling and production.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] After that, a smaller team would be working until the vehicle launch.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] In the early days of the automobile, manufacturers prioritized function over form, focusing on building simple, reliable, and affordable vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Some automakers began incorporating artists to combine styling with engineering.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Visual appeal remained secondary to technical and safety advancements until the 1930s, an era that, despite its financial challenges, became a high point of creative coachbuilding.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] World War II halted the momentum, but it evolved when the industry restarted in the late 1940s, heavily influenced by the Jet Age.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] However, the artwork and models created by designers are routinely destroyed so as not to be seen by competing automakers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Great car designers are visionary artists who can translate their ideas from sketches and models into tangible vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Their work is a blend of artistry and engineering, shaped by collaborations with engineers who help bring their creative concepts to life.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Some automobile forms have served to influence the success and careers of successive designers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] In the United States, automotive design reached a turning point in the 1920s when the American national automobile market began reaching saturation.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] To maintain unit sales, General Motors head Alfred P.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Sloan Jr. suggested annual model-year design changes to convince car owners that they needed to buy a new replacement each year, an idea borrowed from the bicycle industry (though Sloan usually gets the credit or blame).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Critics called his strategy planned obsolescence.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Sloan preferred the term "dynamic obsolescence".
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] This strategy had far-reaching effects on the auto business, the field of product design, and eventually the American economy.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The smaller automakers could not maintain the pace and expense of yearly re-styling.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Henry Ford did not like the model-year change because he clung to an engineer's notions of simplicity, the economics of scale, and design integrity.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] GM surpassed Ford's sales in 1931 and became the dominant company in the industry thereafter.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The frequent design changes also made it necessary to use a body-on-frame rather than the lighter but less adaptable monocoque design used by most European automakers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] In the 1930s, Chrysler's innovations with aerodynamics helped launch the Chrysler Airflow in 1934, which was revolutionary and radical compared to contemporary vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] However, inadequate consumer acceptance of the advanced appearance of the cars forced a re-design of succeeding models of the Airflow.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] This marketing experience made the entire industry take note of the high risks involved in incorporating major design advancements into their production cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] A major influence on American auto styling and marketing was Harley Earl, who is credited with inventing the idea of a concept car, and who brought the tailfin and other aeronautical design references to auto design starting with the rear fenders of the 1948 Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Another notable designer was Chrysler group's designer Virgil Exner, who developed the Forward look design in the mid-1950s.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Exner is also credited with using wind tunnel testing to justify incorporating tailfins, thus moving the company away from boxy-looking cars into more aerodynamic and futuristic designs that were influenced by rockets after WWII.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Other influential automotive designers include Raymond Loewy, who was responsible for a number of Studebaker vehicles such as the Avanti, and Gordon Buehrig, who was responsible for the Auburn 851, as well as the Cord 810 and 812.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Starting in the 1960s, Dick Teague, who spent most of his career with American Motors Corporation (AMC), originated the concept of using interchangeable body panels so as to create a wide array of different vehicles using the same stampings, starting with the AMC Cavalier.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Teague was responsible for automotive designs such as the two-seat AMC AMX muscle car, the subcompact Gremlin, the Pacer, and Matador coupe, as well as the original and market segment-creating, Jeep Cherokee.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Additionally during the 1960s, Ford's first-generation Ford Mustang and Thunderbird marked another era leading into new market segments from Detroit.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The Ford Mustang achieved record sales in its first year of production and established the pony car segment.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Personal injury litigation has affected the design and appearance of the car in the 20th century.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Until World War I, most automakers were concerned with mechanical reliability rather than the external appearance of their cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Later, luxury and aesthetics became a demand, and also an effective marketing tool.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Designs from each nation with their own strong cultural identity are reflected in their exterior and interior designs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] World War II slowed the progress, but after the early 1950s, Italian designers set the trend and remained the driving force until the early part of the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] In France notable designs came from Bugatti and Avions Voisin.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Of the mass-selling cars, Citroën launched their vehicles with innovative designs and engineering, aided by the styling of Flaminio Bertoni as evident from the Citroën DS.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] After World War II, with the decline of the coachbuilding industry, French automakers (except Citroën) followed British and other popular trends until they gained financial stability.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] During the 1980s, manufacturers like Renault cultivated their own strong design identities with designers like Patrick Le Quément.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Peugeot, which was dependent on Pininfarina since the early post-war period, later established its own brand identity from the 1980s onwards.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Its other company, Citroën, still retains its distinctive French innovations for its designs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Great Britain was Europe's leading manufacturer of automobiles until the late-1960s.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] During that era, there were more British-based automakers than in the rest of Europe combined.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The British automobile industry catered to all segments ranging from compact, budget, sports, utility, and luxury-type cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Car design in Britain was markedly different from other European designs largely because British designers were not influenced by other European art or design movements, as well as the British clay modelers, used a different sweep set.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] British cars until World War II were sold in most of the British colonies.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Innovations in vehicle packaging and chassis engineering combined with global familiarity with British designs meant vehicles were acceptable to public tastes at that time.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] British skilled resources such as panel beaters, die machinists, and clay modelers were also available partly due to their involvement with the motorsport industry.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Still, during the 1960s, British manufacturers sought professional help from Italian designers and studios such as Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, and Pininfarina.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Notable British contributions to automobile designs were the Morris Mini by Alec Issigonis, several Jaguar Cars by Sir William Lyons and Malcolm Sayer, Aston Martin DB Series, and several cars from Triumph and MG.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Ford Europe, based in Great Britain, is notable for the Ford Sierra line, a work of Uwe Bahnsen, Robert Lutz, and Patrick le Quément.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Other notable British designers include William Towns for Aston Martin, and David Bache for Land Rover and Range Rover, and Ian Callum for Jaguar.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] During the complex changes in the British car industry in the 1990s and beyond, a mix of designers worked on all of the remaining mainstream brands under one design director and in one studio.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The director most involved was Geoff Upex, with his team of Richard Woolley, Dave Saddington, George Thomson, Alan Mobberley, and Martin Peach (colour and trim).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Germany is often considered the birthplace of industrial design with the Bauhaus School of Design, before it was closed down by the Nazi regime.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Ferdinand Porsche and his family played a significant role in German design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Mercedes-Benz passenger cars were also in the luxury segment and played an important role in German car design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] After the 1980s, German design evolved into a distinctive Teutonic style often to complement their highly engineered cars suited to Autobahns.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The early German design clues of the present-day owe some part to Italian designers like Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, and Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] During the mid- and late-20th century one of the most influential coach builders/designers in Germany was Karmann.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] German designs started gaining popularity after the 1980s, notable after the formation of Audi.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Volkswagen, which was dependent on Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Karmann, later formed the contemporary design language along with Audi.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] BMW entered the automobile design with sporty-looking everyday sedans using Giovanni Michelotti.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] These models were later enhanced by Ercole Spada into the 1980s, and Klaus Luthe until the mid-1990s.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The American-born designer Chris Bangle was hired by BMW in the late-1990s to redefine the brand.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Bangle incorporated new single-press technology for compound curves to add controversial styling elements to his designs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The Porsche family contribution was instrumental in the evolution of Porsche cars, while the Italian designer Bruno Sacco helped create various Mercedes Models from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] In Italy, Fiat and Alfa Romeo played a major role in car design.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Many coachbuilders were dependent on these two major manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Italian manufacturers had a large presence in motorsports leading to several sport car manufacturers like Ferrari, Lancia, Lamborghini, Maserati, etc.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] During the late-1950s, Italian automobile designs gained global popularity coinciding with the modern fashion and architecture at that time around the world.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Various design and technical schools in Turin turned out designers on a large scale.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] By the late-1960s, almost all Italian coachbuilders transformed into design studios catering to automakers around the world.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The trend continued in the 1990s when the Japanese and Korean manufacturers sourced designs from these styling studios.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Some Italian designers whose design services were sought globally include Aldo Brovarone, Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Walter de Silva.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Sweden had Volvo and Saab as domestic automakers, and the nation's northern location required that cars needed to withstand Nordic climate conditions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] The Scandinavian design elements are known for their minimalism and simplicity.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] One of the early original Scandinavian designs was the Saab 92001 by Sixten Sason and Gunnar Ljungström.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Koenigsegg, founded in the 1990s, became Sweden's first domestic producer of high end sports cars, with many of their models featuring in house designs by Swedish designers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Before World War II and until the early-1990s, Czechoslovakia had a strong presence in the automotive industry with manufacturers like Škoda, Jawa, Tatra, CZ, Praga, and Zetor.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] Czech automobiles were generally known for their originality in mechanical simplicity and designs were remarkably Bohemian as evident from Tatra cars and Jawa motorcycles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-design] During the Communist regime, the design started falling back and ultimately the domestic automakers ended up as subsidiaries of EU-based companies.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Many emergency vehicles have distinctive lighting equipment to warn drivers of their presence.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Early road vehicles used fuelled lamps before the availability of electric lighting.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] The first Ford Model T used carbide lamps for headlights and oil lamps for tail lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] It did not have all-electric lighting as a standard feature until several years after its introduction.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Dynamos for automobile headlights were first fitted around 1908 and became commonplace in 1920s automobiles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Trafficators—signalling arms that flipped up, which later were lighted—were introduced in the early 1900s, and were actuated either mechanically or pneumatically.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Tail lights and brake lights were introduced around 1915, and by 1919, low-beam or dipped beam headlights were available.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Sealed beam headlights were introduced in 1936 and standardized as the only acceptable type in the US in 1940.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Self-cancelling turn signals were developed in 1940.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] By 1945, headlights and signal lights were integrated into the body styling.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Halogen headlights were developed in Europe in 1960.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] High-intensity discharge (HID) headlights were produced starting in 1991.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] In 1993, the first LED tail lights were installed on mass-production automobiles, with LED headlights subsequently being introduced in the 2000s as more powerful LEDs became available.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] The colour of light emitted by vehicle lights is largely standardized by established conventions, first codified in the 1949 Geneva Convention on Road Traffic and later specified in the 1968 United Nations Vienna Convention on Road Traffic.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] With some regional exceptions, lights facing rearward must emit red light, side-facing lights and all turn signals must emit amber light, and lights facing forward must emit white or selective yellow light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] No other colours are permitted except on emergency vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Vehicle lighting colour specifications can differ somewhat in countries that have not signed the 1949 and/or 1968 Conventions; examples include turn signals and side marker lights in North America, as described in those lights' sections later in this article.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Forward illumination is provided by high- ("main", "full", "driving") and low- ("dip", "dipped", "passing") beam headlights, which may be augmented by auxiliary fog lights, driving lights, or cornering lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Low beam (also called dipped beam, passing beam, or meeting beam) headlights provide adequate forward and lateral illumination without dazzling other road users with excessive glare.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] This beam is specified for use whenever other vehicles are present ahead.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE regulations for dipped beam headlights specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is flat and low, while the half of the beam closest to the outside of the road slopes up and towards the near side of the roadway.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] This permits a functional compromise where it is possible to substantially prevent glare for oncoming drivers, while still allowing adequate illumination for drivers to see pedestrians, road signs, hazards, etc. on their side of the road.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] The United States and Canada use proprietary FMVSS / CMVSS standards instead of UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] These standards contain regulations for dipped beam headlights that also specify a beam with a sharp, asymmetric cut-off; the half of the beam closest to oncoming drivers is also flat and low, but not as low as prescribed in UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] The half of the beam closest to the outside of the road is also flat, but higher than the half closest to oncoming vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] This results in substantially increased glare for oncoming drivers and also poorer illumination of the near side of the roadway in comparison to headlights conforming to UN ECE regulations.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] High beam (also called main beam, driving beam, or full beam) headlights provide an intense, centre-weighted distribution of light with no particular glare control.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Therefore, they are only suitable for use when alone on the road, as the glare they produce will dazzle other drivers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] UN ECE Regulations permit higher-intensity high-beam headlights than allowed under U.S. and Canadian FMVSS / CMVSS standards.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Auxiliary high beam lights may be fitted to provide high-intensity light to enable the driver to see at longer range than the vehicle's high beam headlights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Such lights are most notably fitted on rally cars, and are occasionally fitted to production vehicles derived from or imitating such cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] They are common in countries with large stretches of unlit roads, or in regions such as the Nordic countries that receive fewer daylight hours during winter.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] "Driving light" is a term hailing from the early days of night time driving, when it was relatively rare to encounter an opposing vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Only on occasions when opposing drivers passed each other would the low (dipped or "passing") beam be used.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] The high beam was therefore known as the "driving beam", and this terminology is still found in international UN Regulations, which do not distinguish between a vehicle's primary (mandatory) and auxiliary (optional) upper/driving beam lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] The "driving light" term has been supplanted in US regulations by the functionally descriptive term "auxiliary high-beam light".
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Many countries regulate the installation and use of driving lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] For example, in Russia, each vehicle may have no more than three pairs of driving lights (including the original lights), and in Paraguay, auxiliary driving lights must be off and covered with opaque material when the vehicle is operated in urban areas.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Front fog lights provide a wide, bar-shaped beam of light with a sharp cutoff at the top, and are generally aimed and mounted low.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] They may produce white or selective yellow light, and were designed for use at low speed to increase the illumination directed towards the road surface and verges in conditions of poor visibility due to fog, dust or snow.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] They are sometimes used in place of dipped-beam headlights, reducing glare from fog or falling snow, although the legality of using front fog lights without low-beam headlights varies by jurisdiction.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] In most countries, weather conditions rarely necessitate the use of front fog lights and there is no legal requirement for them, so their primary purpose is frequently cosmetic.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] They are often available as optional extras or only on higher trim levels of many cars.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Since as early as the 2020s, several car manufacturers have noticeably omitted the front fog lights from many of their latest models, as more recent high-tech lighting technologies such as daytime running lamps (DRLs) and LEDs connected to automatic high-beam systems negate the use of fog lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] However, some manufacturers who still offer fog lights as standard equipment in certain model trims have diversified its use to function also as an automatic lighting delay for vehicles, to light up surroundings and roadside curbs after being parked.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] An SAE study has shown that in the United States, more people inappropriately use their fog lights in dry weather than use them properly in poor weather.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] The respective purposes of front fog lights and driving lights are often confused, due in part to the misconception that fog lights are always selective yellow, while any auxiliary light that makes white light is a driving light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Automakers and aftermarket parts and accessories suppliers frequently refer interchangeably to "fog lights" and "driving lights" (or "fog/driving lights").
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] On some models, cornering lights provide steady-intensity white light for lateral illumination in the direction of an intended turn or lane change.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] They are generally actuated in conjunction with the turn signals, and they may be wired to also illuminate when the vehicle is shifted into reverse gear.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Some modern vehicles activate the cornering light on one or the other side when the steering wheel input reaches a predetermined angle in that direction, regardless of whether a turn signal has been activated.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] American technical standards contain provisions for front cornering lights as well as rear cornering lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Cornering lights have traditionally been prohibited under international UN Regulations, though provisions have recently been made to allow them as long as they are only operable when the vehicle is travelling at less than 40 kilometres per hour (about 25 mph).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p01] Police cars, emergency vehicles, and vehicles competing in road rallies are sometimes equipped with an auxiliary spotlight, sometimes called an "alley light", in a swivel-mounted housing attached to one or both A-pillars, aimed by a handle protruding through the pillar into the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity devices are lights and reflectors that are intended to make a vehicle more conspicuous and visible with respect to its presence, position, direction of travel, change in direction, or deceleration.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Such lights may light steadily, blink, or flash, depending on their intended and regulated function.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Most must be fitted in pairs—one left and one right—though some vehicles have multiple pairs (such as two left and two right stop lights) and/or redundant light sources (such as one left and one right stop light, each containing two bulbs).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Front position lights (known as parking lights in North America and front sidelights in the UK) provide nighttime standing-vehicle conspicuity.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They are designed to use little electricity so they can be left on when parked for prolonged periods of time.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Despite the UK term, these are not the same as the side marker lights described below.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The front position lights on any vehicle must emit white light, with the exception of motorcycles, which may have amber front position lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, Canada, Mexico, Iceland, Japan, New Zealand, and Australia (only if combined with a side marker), South Korea, North Korea, Vietnam, China, Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, and much of the Middle East, they may emit amber light on any vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The "city light" terminology for front position lights derives from the practice, formerly adhered to in cities like Moscow, London and Paris, of driving at night in urban areas using these low-intensity lights rather than the vehicle's headlights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In Germany, the StVZO (Road Traffic Licensing Regulations) calls for a different function provided by these lights: with the vehicle's ignition switched off, the operator may activate a low-intensity white light at the front and red light at the rear on either the left or right side.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This function is used when parking in narrow unlit streets to provide parked-vehicle conspicuity to approaching drivers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This function, which is optional under UN and US regulations, is served passively in the United States by mandatory side marker retroreflectors.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some countries permit or require vehicles to be equipped with daytime running lights (DRLs).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the regulations of the country for which the vehicle is built, these may be functionally dedicated lights, or the function may be provided by the low beam or high beam headlights, the front turn signals, or the front fog lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Passenger cars and small delivery vans first type approved to UN Regulation 48 on or after 7 February 2011, and large vehicles (trucks and buses) type approved since August 2012, must be equipped with DRLs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Functional piggybacking, such as using the headlights, front turn signals, or fog lights as DRLs, is not permitted; the EU Directive requires functionally specific daytime running lights compliant with UN Regulation 87 and mounted to the vehicle in accord with UN Regulation 48.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Prior to the DRL mandate, countries requiring daytime lights permitted low beam headlights to provide that function.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] National regulations in Canada, Sweden, Norway, Slovenia, Finland, Iceland, and Denmark require hardwired automatic DRL systems of varying specification.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] DRLs are permitted in many countries where they are not required, but prohibited in other countries not requiring them.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Front, side, and rear position lights are permitted, required, or forbidden to illuminate in combination with daytime running lights, depending on the jurisdiction and the DRL implementation.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Likewise, according to jurisdictional regulations, DRLs mounted within a certain distance of turn signals are permitted or required to extinguish or dim down to parking light intensity individually when the adjacent turn signal is operating.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 87 stipulates that DRLs must emit white light with an intensity of at least 400 candela on axis and no more than 1200 candela in any direction.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US, daytime running lights may emit either amber or white light, and may produce up to 7,000 candela.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This has provoked a large number of complaints about glare.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] UK regulations briefly required vehicles first used on or after 1 April 1987 to be equipped with a "dim-dip" device or special low-intensity running lights, except such vehicles as complying fully with UN Regulation 48 regarding the installation of lighting equipment.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] A dim-dip device operates the dipped beam headlights at between 10% and 20% of normal low-beam intensity.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Running lights permitted as an alternative to dim-dip were required to emit at least 200 candela straight ahead, and no more than 800 candela in any direction.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In practice, most vehicles were equipped with the dim-dip option rather than dedicated running lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The dim-dip systems were not intended for daytime use as DRLs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather, they operated if the engine was running *and* the driver switched on the position lights (called sidelights in the UK).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The UK was the only country to require such dim-dip systems, though vehicles so equipped were sold in other Commonwealth countries with left-hand traffic.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1988, the European Commission successfully prosecuted the UK government in the European Court of Justice, arguing that the UK requirement for dim-dip was illegal under EC directives prohibiting member states from enacting vehicle lighting requirements not contained in pan-European EC directives.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] As a result, the UK requirement for dim-dip was quashed.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Nevertheless, dim-dip systems remain permitted, and while such systems are not presently as common as they once were, dim-dip functionality was fitted on many new cars well into the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States, amber front and red rear side marker lights and retroreflectors are required.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The law initially required lights *or* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1968.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This was amended to require lights *and* retroreflectors on vehicles manufactured after 1 January 1970.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These side-facing devices make the vehicle's presence, position and direction of travel clearly visible from oblique angles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The lights are wired to illuminate whenever the vehicles' parking lights and tail lights are on, including when the headlights are being used.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Front amber side markers in the United States may be wired to flash in synchronous phase or opposite-phase with the turn signals; nevertheless, they are not required to flash at all.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Side markers are permitted but not required on cars and light passenger vehicles outside the United States and Canada.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These were sometimes used in tandem with fender lights during the same time period, when fenders were separate from the body and only covered the wheels.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They are activated by the driver on one side of the vehicle at a time to advertise intent to turn or change lanes towards that side, or used simultaneously as a hazard warning signal to warn other drivers of a vehicle parked on the road (see below).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] For many years, turn signals' on-off operation was activated by a thermal flasher unit which used a heating element, leaf spring, and a bimetallic strip.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] When activated by the stalk switch on the steering column, the signal lights and heating element turned on.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The heat caused the bimetallic strip to bend such that it threw the leaf spring over centre, opening the circuit and breaking power to the heating element and the signal lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] When the bimetallic strip cooled down, it would pull the leaf spring back over centre in the other direction, closing the contacts and again sending power to the lights and heating element.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The cycle would repeat until the power to the thermal flasher was switched off by the stalk switch.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Thermal flashers gradually gave way to electromechanical relays; one of many control strategies with relay-type flashers is to use a relaxation oscillator chip to generate square waves to the relay coil, causing the relay contacts to open and close.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern cars now use a relaxation oscillator and solid-state relay built into the body control module to flash the lights, and use speakers to produce the distinctive clicking sound associated with turn signals, which was previously made by a relay or the leaf spring in a thermal flasher.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] If the stalk switch is not moved beyond the fixed left/right position and allowed to flip back, the control module will only flash the lights three times.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Electric turn signal lights date from as early as 1907.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In 1908, Alfredo Barrachini in Rome added electric lights inside the arms that turned on as they extended, but operation was still by a cable system.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] An early patent for a new style of turn signal was issued in 1909 to a British man named Percy Douglas-Hamilton, who came up with a system that used a hand on each side of the car, which could be illuminated to indicate a coming turn.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Silent film star Florence Lawrence is also credited with introducing an innovative version of the signalling arm in 1914, a predecessor to the modern turn signal, and a mechanical brake signal.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] She did not patent these inventions, however, and received no credit or profit from them.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Possibly the first factory installation of illuminated turn signals was on the Talbot 105 (as well as the 75 and 95), which used them at the front as well as at the rear from 1932 until 1935.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The modern flashing turn signal was patented in 1938, and shortly after, most major automobile manufacturers offered this optional feature before it became mandatory in 1967.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] As of 2013, most countries require turn signals on all new vehicles that are driven on public roadways.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Alternative systems of hand signals were used earlier and remain common for bicycles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Hand signals are also sometimes used when regular vehicle lights are malfunctioning or for older vehicles without turn signals.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some cars from about 1900 to through 1966 used retractable semaphores called trafficators rather than flashing lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They were commonly mounted high up behind the front doors and swung out to a horizontal position.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They were fragile and could be easily broken off, and also had a tendency to stick in the closed or open position.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They could be fitted with a fixed or flashing light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] After turn signals were introduced regulations were brought in requiring them and laying out specifications that had to be met.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In most countries, cars must be equipped with side-mounted turn signal repeaters to make the turn indication visible laterally (i.e. to the sides of the vehicle) rather than just to the front and rear of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These are permitted, but not required in the United States and Canada.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] As an alternative in both the United States and Canada, the front amber side marker lights may be wired to flash with the turn signals, but this is not mandatory.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Mercedes-Benz introduced side turn signal repeaters integrated into the side-view mirrors in 1998, starting with its facelifted E-Class (W210).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Since then, many automakers have been incorporating side turn signal devices into the mirror housings rather than mounting them on the vehicle's fenders.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some evidence suggests that mirror-mounted turn signals may be more effective than fender-mounted ones.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are required to blink on and off, or "flash", at a steady rate of between 60 and 120 pulses per minute (1–2 Hz).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations require that all turn signals flash in simultaneous phase; US regulations permit side marker lights wired for side turn signal functionality to flash in opposite-phase.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] An audio and/or visual tell-tale indicator is required, to advise the driver when the turn signals are activated and operating.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This usually takes the form of one green light on the dashboard on cars from the 1950s or older, or two green indicator lights on cars from the 1960s to the present, and a rhythmic ticking sound generated electromechanically or electronically by the flasher.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] It is also required that the vehicle operator be alerted by much faster- or slower-than-normal flashing in the event a turn signal light fails.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Turn signals are, in almost every case, activated by a horizontal stalk protruding from the side of the steering column, though on some vehicles it protrudes from the dashboard.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The driver raises or lowers the outboard end of the stalk in accord with the clockwise or anticlockwise direction the steering wheel is about to be turned.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In left-hand drive vehicles, the turn indicator stalk is usually located to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In right-hand-drive vehicles, there is less consistency; it may be located to the left or to the right of the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations do not specify a mandatory location for the turn signal control, only that it be visible and operable by the driver, and—at least in North America—that it be labelled with a specific symbol if it is not located on the left side of the steering column.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The international UN Regulations do not include analogous specifications.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Virtually all vehicles (except many motorcycles and commercial semi-tractors) have a turn indicator self-cancelling feature that returns the lever to the neutral (no signal) position as the steering wheel approaches the straight-ahead position after a turn has been made.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Beginning in the late 1960s, using the direction-indicator lights to signal for a lane change was facilitated by the addition of a spring-loaded momentary signal-on position just shy of the left and right detents.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The signal operates for however long the driver holds the lever partway towards the left or right turn signal detent.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have an automatic lane-change indication feature; tapping the lever partway towards the left or right signal position and immediately releasing it causes the applicable turn indicators to flash three to five times.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some transit buses, such as those in New York, have turn signals activated by floor-mounted momentary-contact footswitches on the floor near the driver's left foot (on left-hand drive buses).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The foot-activated signals allow bus drivers to keep both hands on the steering wheel while watching the road and scanning for passengers as they approach a bus stop.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] New York City Transit bus drivers, among others, are trained to step continuously on the right directional switch while servicing a bus stop, to signal other road users they are intentionally dwelling at the stop, allowing following buses to skip that stop.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This method of signalling requires no special arrangements for self-cancellation or passing.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Sequential turn signals are a feature on some cars, wherein the turn signal function is provided by multiple lit elements that illuminate sequentially rather than simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The visual effect is one of outward motion in the direction of the intended turn or lane change.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The earlier, fitted to the 1965 through 1968 Ford-built cars and the 1971–1972 Nissan Cedric, employed an electric motor driving, through reduction gearing, a set of three slow-turning cams.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These cams would actuate switches to turn on the lights in sequence.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Later Ford cars and the 1969 Imperial used a transistorised control module with no moving parts to wear, break, or go out of adjustment.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] FMVSS 108 has been officially interpreted as requiring all light sources in an active turn signal to illuminate simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles, such as the 2010 and later Ford Mustang, are designed such that the first lit segment of the multi-unit light is considered as the official turn signal, with the segments illuminated afterward considered as auxiliary lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Other US vehicles with sequential turn signals comply by illuminating all elements of the turn signal simultaneously, before sequentially turning them off.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Until the early 1960s, most front turn signals worldwide emitted white light and most rear turn signals emitted red light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Currently, most countries outside the United States and Canada require that all front, side and rear turn signals produce amber light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In Belgium, Brazil, Canada, the GCC countries, Israel, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Switzerland, and the US, the rear signals may be amber or red.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Additionally, red turn signals can also be found in countries with trade agreements with the US such as Mexico and South Korea, and New Zealand.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of red rear turn signals have claimed that they are less costly to manufacture, and automakers use the turn signal colour as a styling element to differentiate vehicles of different model years.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of amber rear turn signals say they are more easily discernible as turn signals.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] It has been recognised since the 1960s that amber turn signals are more quickly spotted than red ones.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] There is some evidence that turn signals with colourless clear lenses and amber bulbs may be less conspicuous in bright sunlight than those with amber lenses and colourless bulbs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The amber bulbs commonly used in turn signals with colourless lenses are no longer made with cadmium glass, since various regulations worldwide, including the European RoHS directive, banned cadmium because of its toxicity.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Amber glass made without cadmium is relatively costly, so most amber bulbs are now made with clear glass dipped in an amber coating.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] With accumulated heat-cool cycles, though, some of these coatings may flake off the bulb glass, or the colour may fade.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This causes the turn signal to emit white light rather than the required amber light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The international regulation on motor vehicle bulbs requires manufacturers to test bulbs for colour endurance.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] However, no test protocol or colour durability requirement is specified.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Discussion is ongoing within the *Groupe des Rapporteurs d'Éclairage*, the UNECE working group on vehicular lighting regulation, to develop and implement a colour durability standard.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Rather than using an amber bulb, some signal lights contain an inner amber plastic enclosure between a colourless bulb and the colourless outer lens or by using integrated amber LEDs in a colourless enclosure which produces less heat.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Conspicuity for the rear of a vehicle is provided by rear position lights (also called tail lights).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These are required to produce only red light and to be wired such that they are lit whenever the front position lights are lit, including when the headlights are on.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear position lights may be combined with the vehicle's stop lights or be separate from them.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In combined-function installations, the lights produce brighter red light as stop lights and dimmer red light as rear position lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide stipulate minimum intensity ratios between the bright (stop) and dim (position) modes, so that a vehicle displaying rear position lights will not be mistakenly interpreted as showing stop lights and vice versa.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Red steadily lit rear lights, brighter than the rear position lights, are activated when the driver applies the vehicle's brakes and warn vehicles behind to prepare to stop.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These are formally called "stop lamps" in technical standards and regulations and in the Vienna Convention on Road Traffic, though they are often informally called brake lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They are required to be fitted in multiples of two, symmetrically at the left and right edges of the rear of every vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] 7 specify a range of acceptable intensity for a stop light of 60 to 185 candela.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where the UN regulations are not recognised, the acceptable range for a single-compartment stop light is 80 to 300 candela.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and Canada since 1986, in Australia and New Zealand since 1990, and in Europe and other countries applying UN Regulation 48 since 1998, a central stop (brake) light mounted higher than the vehicle's left and right stop lights is also required.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The so-called "centre high mount stop lamp", or **CHMSL** (pronounced /ˈtʃɪmzəl/), is sometimes informally called the "centre brake light", the "third brake light", the "eye-level brake light", the "safety brake light", or the "high-level brake light".
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL may use one or more filament bulbs or LEDs, or a strip of neon tubing as its light source.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is intended to provide a warning to drivers whose view of the vehicle's left and right stop lights is blocked by interceding vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] It also provides a redundant stop light signal in the event of a stop light malfunction.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In North America, where rear turn signals are permitted to emit red light, the CHMSL also helps to differentiate brake lights from rear position lights and turn signal lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] On passenger cars, the CHMSL may be placed above the back glass, affixed to the vehicle's interior just inside the back glass, or integrated into the vehicle's deck lid or into a spoiler.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Other specialised fitments are sometimes seen; the Jeep Wrangler and Land Rover Freelander have the CHMSL on a stalk fixed to the spare wheel carrier.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Trucks, vans, and commercial vehicles sometimes have the CHMSL mounted to the trailing edge of the vehicle's roof.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The CHMSL is required by regulations worldwide to be centred laterally on the vehicle, though UN Regulation 48 permits lateral offset of up to 15 cm if the vehicle's lateral centre is not coincident with a fixed body panel, but instead separates movable components such as doors.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Such an offset can be seen on the third-generation Renault Master and first-generation Ford Transit Connect vans.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The height of the CHMSL is also regulated, both in absolute terms and with respect to the mounting height of the vehicle's conventional left and right stop lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on the left and right lights' height, the lower edge of the CHMSL may be just above the left and right lights' upper edge.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1952 Volkswagen Bus was equipped with only one stop light, mounted centrally and higher than the left and right rear lights, which did not produce a stop light function.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The 1968–1971 Ford Thunderbird could be ordered with optional supplemental high-mounted stop and turn signal lights integrated into the left and right interior trim surrounding the rear glass.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The Oldsmobile Toronado (from 1971 to 1978) and the Buick Riviera (from 1974 to 1976) had similar dual high-mounted supplemental stop/turn lights as standard equipment; these were located on the outside of the vehicle below the bottom of the rear glass.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of configuration was not widely adopted at the time.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Car and lighting manufacturers in Germany experimented with dual high-mount supplemental stop lights in the early 1980s, but this effort, too, failed to gain wide popular or regulatory support.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Effective with the 1986 model year, the United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada mandated that all new passenger cars come equipped with a CHMSL.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The requirement was extended to light trucks and vans for the 1994 model year.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Early studies involving taxicabs and other fleet vehicles found that a third high-level stop light reduced rear-end collisions by about 50%.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Once the novelty effect wore off as most vehicles on the road came to be equipped with a CHMSL, the crash-avoidance benefit declined.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] However, said benefit has not declined to zero, and a CHMSL has become so inexpensive to incorporate into a vehicle that it remains a cost-effective collision avoidance feature even at the long-term enduring crash-reduction benefit of 4.3%.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] A NHTSA report suggests that a vehicle equipped with a CHMSL has 23.7% less risk to be involved as a lead vehicle in a chain collision and 16.0% less risk to be involved as a middle vehicle in such a collision.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency stop signalling is a lighting function wherein the vehicle's stop (brake) lights and/or hazard/turn indicators flash in phase at 3 to 5 Hz under heavy or urgent braking.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The emergency stop signal is automatically activated if the vehicle speed is greater than 50 km/h (31 mph) and the emergency braking logic defined by regulation No.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In February 2019, members of the European Parliament approved rules making emergency stop signals mandatory on new vehicles sold in the European Union.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Toyota, Mercedes-Benz, Volvo and BMW were among the earlier automakers to begin equipping vehicles with ESS.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2013, Kia introduced the concept on some of their Australian-market models.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Other methods of severe braking indication have also been implemented; some Volvo models make the stop lights brighter, and some BMWs have "Adaptive Brake Lights" that effectively increase the size of the stop lights under severe braking by illuminating them at brighter-than-normal intensity.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] As long as the brighter-than-normal stop lights are within the regulated maximum intensity for stop lights in general, this kind of implementation does not require specific regulatory approval, since the stop lights continue to operate in accord with general stop light regulations.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The idea behind such emergency braking indicator systems is to catch following drivers' attention with increased urgency.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] However, there remains considerable debate over whether the system offers a measurable increase in safety.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] To date, studies of vehicles with ESS have not shown significant improvement.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The systems used by BMW, Volvo, and Mercedes differ not only in operational mode (growing vs. intensifying vs. flashing, respectively), but also in such parameters as the deceleration threshold of activation.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Data is being collected and analyzed in an effort to determine how such a system might be implemented to maximize a safety benefit, if such a benefit can be realized with visual emergency braking displays.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] An experimental study at the University of Toronto has tested stop lights which gradually and continuously grow in illuminated area with increasing braking.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The ESS is not expensive because it reuses existing warning and stop signals.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] One potential problem with flashing stop lights in the United States and Canada is regulations that permit flashing stop lights to be used as rear turn signal and hazard lights, in lieu of separate dedicated lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In Europe and other countries adhering to UN Regulation 48, vehicles must be equipped with one or two bright red "rear fog lamps", which serve as high-intensity rear position lights to be activated in poor visibility conditions to make the vehicle more visible from the rear.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The allowable range of intensity for a rear fog light is 150 to 300 candela, within the range of a US stop light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Rear fog lights are not required equipment in the US, but they are permitted, and they are found almost exclusively on European-brand vehicles in North America.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Audi, Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz, Mini, Land Rover, Porsche, Saab, and Volvo provide functional rear fog lights on their North American models.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles from non-European brands which are adaptions of European-market offerings, such as the first-generation Ford Transit Connect, have come standard with rear fog lights, or vehicles with European-market counterparts, such as the second generation Chrysler 300, have an option for them.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The second generation Oldsmobile Aurora also had dual rear fog lights installed in the rear bumper as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Most jurisdictions permit rear fog lights to be installed either singly or in pairs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] If a single rear fog is fitted, most jurisdictions require it to be located at or to the driver's side of the vehicle's centreline—whichever side is the prevailing driver's side in the country in which the vehicle is registered.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This is to maximise the sight line of following drivers to the rear fog light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In many cases, a single reversing light is mounted on the passenger side of the vehicle, positionally symmetrical with the rear fog.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] If two rear fog lights are fitted, they must be symmetrical with respect to the vehicle's centreline.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of twin rear fog lights say two lights provide vehicle distance information not available from a single light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Proponents of the single rear fog light say dual rear fog lights closely mimic the appearance of illuminated stop lights (which are mandatorily installed in pairs), reducing the conspicuity of the stop lights' message when the rear fogs are activated.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] To provide some safeguard against rear fog lights being confused with stop lights, UN Regulation 48 requires a separation of at least 10 cm between the closest illuminated edges of any stop light and any rear fog light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] To warn adjacent vehicle operators and pedestrians of a vehicle's rearward motion, and to provide illumination to the rear when reversing, each vehicle must be equipped with one or two rear-mounted, rear-facing reversing (or "backup") lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Reversing lights are required to produce white light by US and international UN regulations.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] However, some countries have at various times permitted amber reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In Australia and New Zealand, for example, vehicle manufacturers were faced with the task of localizing American cars originally equipped with combination red brake/turn signal lights and white reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Both countries now require white reversing lights, and the combination amber turn/reverse light is no longer permitted on new vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The US state of Washington currently permits reversing lights to emit white or amber light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some car models, such as some Saabs have white reversing lights in the front turn indicators that switch on with the rear reversing lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The rear registration plate is illuminated either by a single or a pair of yellow or white light(s), affixed within the indentation of the trunk or bumper.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] It is designed to light the surface of the plate without creating light directly visible to the rear of the vehicle, and must be illuminated whenever the position lights are lit.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Large vehicles such as trucks and buses are in many cases required to carry additional lighting devices beyond those required on passenger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The specific requirements vary according to the regulations in force where the vehicle is registered.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US and Canada, vehicles over 80 inches (2.032 m) wide must be equipped with three amber front and three red rear identification lights spaced 6–12 inches (15–30 cm) apart at the centre of the front and rear of the vehicle, as high as practicable.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The front identification lights are typically mounted atop the cab of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The purpose of these lights is to alert other drivers to the presence of a wide (and usually tall) vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] UN Regulation 48 requires vehicles exceeding 2.10 metres (83 in) in width to be equipped with white front and red rear end-outline marker lights on both the left and right, which, like North American identification lights, are intended to indicate a vehicle's overall width and height.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The front clearance lights may be amber in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] US and Canadian regulations require large vehicles to be equipped with amber side marker lights and reflectors mounted midway between the front and rear side markers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Australian Design Rule 45/01 provides for side marker lights on trucks and other large vehicles producing amber light to the front and red to the rear with no requirement to emit light to the side.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Until about the 1970s in France, Spain, Morocco, and possibly other countries, many commercial vehicles and some Soviet Sovtransavto road trains had a green light mounted on the rear offside.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This could be operated by the driver to indicate that it was safe for the following vehicle to overtake.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The hazard warning signal (sometimes called "hazard warning flashers", "hazard warning lights", "emergency lights", "4-way flashers", "hazards", or "flashers") is provided by flashing all of a vehicle's left and right turn signals simultaneously and in phase.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Hazard warning signals first appeared as aftermarket accessories in the early 1950s; by the late 1960s, regulations around the world came to require all new vehicles to be so equipped.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Operation of the warning signals must be from a control independent of the turn signal control, and an audiovisual tell-tale must be provided to the driver.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In most vehicles, the hazard warning signals can be switched on and off with a physical push-button, which is typically marked with a triangular symbol, symbolizing a warning triangle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with separate left and right green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, both left and right indicators may flash to provide a visual indication of the hazard flashers' operation.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In vehicles with a single green turn signal tell-tale on the dashboard, a separate red tell-tale must be provided for hazard flasher indication.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Because the hazard flasher function operates the vehicle's left and right turn signals, a left or a right turn signal function may not be provided while the hazard flashers are operating.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Apart from its use as emergency lighting, a single flash of the hazard lights is used to show gratitude to yielding drivers in several countries.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] However, in the United Kingdom, they must not be used except to warn others of either a temporary obstruction when the vehicle is stationary or a hazard ahead on a dual carriageway with a speed limit of at least 50 mph.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] "Retroreflectors" (also called "reflex reflectors") produce no light of their own, but rather reflect incident light towards its source, such as another driver's headlights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They are regulated as automotive lighting devices, and specified to account for the separation between a vehicle's headlights and its driver's eyes.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Thus, vehicles can remain conspicuous even with their lights off.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations worldwide require all vehicles and trailers to be equipped with rear-facing red retroreflectors; in countries where UN Regulation No.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] 48 is applied, these must be triangular on trailers and non-triangular on vehicles other than trailers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Since 1968, US regulations also require side-facing retroreflectors, amber in front and red in the rear.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Sweden, South Africa, and other countries have at various times required white front-facing retroreflectors.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] International UN Regulations explicitly permit vehicle signal lights with intensity automatically increased during bright daylight hours when sunlight reduces the effectiveness of the stop lights, and automatically decreased during hours of darkness when glare could be a concern.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Regulations in the US and by the UN contain provisions for determining the minimum and maximum acceptable intensity for lights that contain more than a single light source.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some jurisdictions, such as the US states of Washington, Oregon and Idaho, permit vehicles to be equipped with auxiliary rear signal systems displaying a green light when the accelerator is depressed, yellow light when the vehicle is coasting, and red light when the brake is depressed.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Such systems have in the past been sold as aftermarket accessories, but are today seldom seen in traffic.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Since the late 1960s, there have been proposals to introduce a front-mounted brake light, where green or blue lights would indicate to pedestrians at crossings that an approaching vehicle is slowing down.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] A small subjective survey was undertaken in the US in 1971.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In 2014, the idea was suggested by Slovak Lubomír Marjak (of manufacturing company Lumaco, which makes front brake lights) to German EU parliamentarian Dieter-Lebrecht Koch.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Field tests were done in Germany in 2017, as well as in Slovakia in 2022 and 2023.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Expert analysts have found severe flaws in these tests and the accompanying safety claims.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The only production car to feature a built-in front brake light (as of 2023) was the Bricklin SV-1 of 1974.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, among other bodies, has commissioned studies of vehicle signal systems and configurations to determine the most promising avenues and best practices for enhanced crash avoidance via optimized vehicle conspicuity and signal lighting systems.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Most cars have at least one "dome light" (or "courtesy light") located in or near the ceiling of the passenger compartment, to provide illumination by which to fasten seatbelts and enter or exit the car.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These often have an option to automatically switch on when the front (or any) passenger doors are opened.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Many vehicles have expanded this feature, causing the overhead interior light to remain on after all doors are closed, allowing passengers to fasten seat belts with added illumination.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The extended lighting cycle usually ends when the vehicle's ignition has begun, or a gradual reduction in light emitted after a couple of minutes if the car is not started, called "theater" lighting.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Interior lighting has been added on some vehicles at the bottom edge of the dashboard, illuminating the floor for front passengers, or underneath the front seats at the rear, illuminating the floor for rear passengers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] This type of convenience lighting approach is also sometimes used to illuminate interior or exterior door handles, exterior step running boards, or electric window switches.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] LED light sources appear increasingly as interior convenience lights in various locations, especially with finely focused lighting on console control surfaces and in cabin storage areas.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Map lights are aimed at specific passenger positions and allow for reading without glare distraction to the driver.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some vehicles have "approach lighting" or "puddle lights" (lights that illuminate the ground outside the doors) in the exterior mirrors or lower edges of the doors, as well as interior lighting activated via key fob.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Many cars have lights in the trunk, the engine compartment, the glove box, and other storage compartments.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Modern pickup trucks usually have one or more white cargo lights that illuminate the bed of the truck, often controlled in conjunction with the interior dome lighting.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Most gauges and controls on a dashboard in modern vehicles are illuminated when the headlights are turned on, and the intensity of light can be adjusted by the driver for comfort.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Saab automobiles, for example, have an aircraft-style "night panel" function that shuts off all interior illumination save for the speedometer (unless attention is called to a critical situation on another gauge) to improve the driver's night vision.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Emergency vehicles such as fire engines, ambulances, police cars, snow-removal vehicles and tow trucks are usually equipped with intense warning lights of particular colours.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] These may be motorised rotating beacons, xenon strobes, or arrays of LEDs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] The prescribed colours differ by jurisdiction; in most countries, blue and red special warning lights are used on police, fire, and medical-emergency vehicles.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the United States and some other jurisdictions, amber lights are for tow trucks, private security personnel, construction vehicles, and other nonofficial special-service vehicles, while volunteer firefighters use red, blue, or green, depending on jurisdiction.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the US it is a violation of the DOT (Department of Transportation) Uniform Vehicle Code for any non-emergency vehicle (Police/Fire/Ambulance) to operate forward-facing red lights of any kind.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Some US states allow emergency vehicles to have blue lights that can be turned on to warn drivers of an emergency vehicle in action; blue and red lights can be combined, forward- and/or rear-facing.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] In the UK, doctors may use green warning lights; although these do not allow the user to claim any exemption from road traffic regulations (compared to the blue lights used by statutory emergency services when responding to calls).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Special warning lights, usually amber, are also sometimes mounted on slow or wide vehicles such as mobile cranes, excavators, tractors, and even mobility scooters in certain conditions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Standard taxicabs for street hire are distinguished by special lights affixed to the vehicle's roof in accordance with local regulations.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] They may have an illuminated "Taxi" sign, a light to signal that they are ready to take passengers, or off duty, or an emergency panic light the driver can activate in the event of a robbery to alert passersby to call the police.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p02] Depending on local regulations, the "Taxi" sign may also be required to display a number identifying the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The incandescent light bulb was for a long time the only light source used in automotive lighting.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Incandescent bulbs are still commonly used in turn signals to stop hyper-flashing of the turn signal flashers.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Standardized type numbers are used by manufacturers to identify bulbs with the same specifications.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Bases may be bayonet-type with one or two contacts, plastic or glass wedges, or dual wire loops or ferrules used on tubular "festoon" lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Screw-base lights are never used in automobile applications due to their loosening under vibration.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Signal lights with internal or external coloured lenses use colourless bulbs; conversely, lights with colourless lenses may use red or amber bulbs to provide light of the required colours for the various functions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Tungsten-halogen lights are a very common light source for headlights and other forward illumination functions.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Some recent vehicles use small halogen bulbs for exterior signalling and marking functions, as well.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The first halogen light approved for automotive use was the H1, which used 55 watts producing 1500 lumens and was introduced in Europe in 1962.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Since 1993, light-emitting diodes (LEDs) have increasingly been used in automotive lighting.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] They offer a very long service life, extreme vibration resistance, high colour durability, high efficiency (lumen/Watt) and can benefit from considerably more compact packaging compared to most bulb-type assemblies.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs also offer a potential safety benefit when employed in stop lights; when power is applied, they rise to full intensity approximately 250 milliseconds (¼ second) faster than incandescent bulbs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] This effectively instant rise time theoretically provides following drivers more time to react to the stop light signal, but has not been shown to make cars with LED stop lights less likely to be struck from behind.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] LEDs were first applied to automotive lighting in centre high-mount stop lamps (CHMSLs), beginning with the 1986 Chevrolet Corvette (C4).
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Adoption of LEDs for other signal functions on passenger cars is gradually increasing with demand for the technology and related styling updates.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The first car registered to drive on the road with full LED rear lights was Land Rover's LCV 2/3 concept car in the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] At the time, the only light function that was difficult to reproduce was the reverse light, as white LEDs did not yet exist.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The reverse function was only achievable with the introduction of blue LEDs; by mixing red, green and blue LEDs in a defined distributed pattern behind a lens, white light was produced that conformed to the legal requirements of a reverse light.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The Maserati 3200GT, introduced in 1999, was the first production car to use full LED taillights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] In North America, the 2000 Cadillac Deville was the first passenger car with LED taillights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2002 Kia Opirus was an early adopter of LED front turn signals.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The 2007 Audi R8 used two strips of optically focused high-intensity LEDs for its daytime running lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Optional on the R8 outside North America were the world's first LED headlights, made by AL-Automotive Lighting.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The low and high beams, along with the position (parking) light and front turn signal, all use LEDs.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The Lexus LS 600h (XF40) features LED low beam, position and side marker lights in North America, and the 2009 Cadillac Escalade Platinum used LEDs for the low and high beams, as well as for the position and side marker lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W222) used entirely LED lights, even in the most basic trim level.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lights are used for flashing beacon lights on vehicles such as maintenance trucks.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Previously, traditional light sources required the engine to continue running to ensure that the battery would not become depleted if the lights were to be used for more than a few hours.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] The energy-efficient nature of LEDs allows them to continue flashing with the engine off.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] LED lighting systems are sensitive to heat.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Due to the negative influences of heat on the stability of photometric performance and the light transmitting components, the importance of thermal design, stability tests, usage of low-UV-type LED modules and UV-resistance tests of internal materials has increased dramatically.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] For this reason, LED signal lights must remain compliant with the intensity requirements for the functions they produce after one minute and after thirty minutes of continuous operation.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] In addition, UN Regulation 112 contains a set of tests for LED modules, including colour rendering, UV radiation, and temperature stability tests.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] According to UN Regulations 112 and 123, mechanical, electromechanical or other devices for headlights must withstand endurance tests and function failure tests.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] High-intensity discharge, or HID lights, sometimes referred to as "xenon lights", are modified metal halide lights employing xenon fill gas.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Traditional HID lights, such as those used for general lighting, have a long warm-up time.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Headlights must provide light very shortly after they are turned on, and the xenon gas serves to reduce warm-up time.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon light tubes were introduced into series production for the centre high-mount stop light on the 1995 Ford Explorer.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Notable later uses included the 1998 Lincoln Mark VIII with a neon tube spanning the width of the trunk decklid, and the BMW Z8, which made extensive use of neon.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Neon lights offer the same nearly instant rise time as LEDs, but require a high-voltage ballast.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] In December 2023, Mercedes-Benz received approval in California and Nevada, the only states where it is legal to operate their self-driving vehicles, for turquoise lights in accordance with SAE standard J3134, to indicate to outside observers that the car's self-driving system is engaged.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Mercedes is the first car manufacturer to equip their self-driving vehicles with such lights.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] In distributive light systems, the light from a single source is sent via optical fibres or light guides to wherever it is needed in the automobile.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Light guides are commonly used to distributively light dashboard displays, and premium vehicles are beginning to use distributive systems for lighting such items as door locks, window controls, and cup holders.
[src:chrysler-newport/automotive-lighting-p03] Distributive exterior lighting has also been explored, with high-intensity central light sources.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Known as the "City of Murals", Belvidere is home to several public art installations throughout the North and South State Street historic districts, which are on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] These historic districts are home to the Boone County Museum of History, the Funderburg House Museum, several restaurants and bars, and antique and boutique stores.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Popular festivities like Heritage Days are held yearly.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Before the arrival of the mostly Anglo-Americans in the 19th century, this area was long occupied by the Illinois Confederation, a loose grouping of up to 12 to 15 Native American tribes.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The main tribes were the Cahokia, Kaskaskia, Michigamea, Peoria, and Tamaroa.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] After trading, warfare and other encounters with French traders, who entered this area before the Anglo-Americans, their numbers declined.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] In large part due to the high mortality from new infectious diseases, which adversely affected Native Americans across the continent.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The area developed as Belvidere was first settled by European Americans in 1835: Simon P.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] They named this location next to the Kishwaukee River as "Elysian Fields" from Greek mythology.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Because new residents could not pronounce or spell the proposed name, the city was eventually renamed after Belvidere, Virginia, the former home of Ebenezer Polk, a railroad lawyer and major financial founder in the city.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere originally developed on the north side of the Kishwaukee River.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] In 1851 the Galena and Chicago Union Railroad was built south of the river, stimulating the relocation of much of the business section to the south side of the river, giving access to railway transportation.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere's downtown is now on the south side.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Major industries developed along the river and railroad, including the National Sewing Machine Company, which operated here from 1886 to the 1940s.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] In 1906, former female sheriff Sarah Ames moved to South Dakota; she named the area where she settled after her home town.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere, South Dakota still operates as a small town in Jackson County.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] On April 21, 1967, a devastating tornado struck Belvidere.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Twenty-four people died as a result, many of them schoolchildren.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The F4 tornado struck at the end of the school day of Belvidere High School, when many children, including those who attended area grade schools, were waiting outside the high school for school buses.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Of the sixteen school buses outside the high school, twelve were overturned or thrown by the tornado.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The tornado did $22 million in damage, demolished over 100 homes, and injured 500 people.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] In 2007 a statue was erected in front of Belvidere High School in memorial of the lives lost.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] As of 2013, the Belvidere tornado was the sixth worst weather disaster to happen at an American school, and the deadliest since 1955.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] On December 7, 2009, an explosion occurred at an NDK America building, when a large pressure vessel ruptured during a crystal-growing process.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Pieces of debris, some weighing several tons, were flung over a wide area.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] One piece struck an automotive supply building and injured an employee inside.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Chesterfield, Indiana native Ronald Greenfield, a truck driver refueling at the nearby Belvidere Oasis truck stop, was struck and killed by a 7-foot support beam.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The shockwave was felt over a wide area.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] No NDK employees were injured in the incident.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The Chemical Safety Board investigated the incident, issuing their final report in 2013.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The CSB found that stress corrosion cracking had occurred, unnoticed, in one of the crystal-growing autoclaves, leading to the catastrophic failure.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] They also found that NDK management had been warned multiple times over the years that the dangerous levels of hot sodium hydroxide inside the vessels would corrode the steel walls.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] However, NDK management insisted buildup of byproducts from the crystal-growing process would passivate the vessel walls against the corrosion.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] However, the vessel that ruptured had never been internally inspected to test the passivation theory, during its many years of service.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] After a smaller leak occurred in January 2007, NDK was warned about safety concerns again, this time by insurance investigators, who were ultimately ignored.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Finally, the CSB determined the method for growing crystals used at NDK's Belvidere facility was prohibitively dangerous in the first place, pointing out such methods had been already abandoned by other crystal-growing facilities in favor of safer, lower-pressure and lower temperature processes.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] Following their own 2010 investigation, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration fined NDK more than half a million dollars for willful disregard for legal requirements, and "unacceptable" indifference to safety and health.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The NDK facility was demolished in 2015, with no plans to rebuild.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] On March 31, 2023, an EF1 tornado struck Belvidere.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] It caused the Apollo Theatre to collapse during a concert for the Floridian Death Metal band Morbid Angel and Brazilian Death Metal band Crypta.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The concert proceeded despite advanced notice of severe conditions expected that day.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] The collapse led to over 40 injuries; leaving at least four in critical condition and one fatality.
[src:chrysler-newport/belvidere-illinois] According to the 2021 census gazetteer files, Belvidere has a total area of 12.30 square miles (31.86 km2), of which 12.06 square miles (31.24 km2) (or 98.08%) is land and 0.24 square miles (0.62 km2) (or 1.92%) is water.
